<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from NCVO [CEP0014]</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About NCVO</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The National Council for Voluntary Organisations champions and strengthens the voluntary sector, with over 10,000 members, from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">largest charities to the smallest community organisations. Alongside our sister councils in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland, we make sure the voluntary sector can do what it does best.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://www.ncvo-vol.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.ncvo-vol.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ummary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">For some time the issue of senior executive salaries across all sectors has been an area of public and political debate.  In response, and following the media articles that appeared over the summer, NCVO has set up an Inquiry into Executive Pay.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e members of the Inquiry Panel represent a cross-section of charities, as well as remuneration and other specialists, and they are independent of NCVO.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Inquiry is currently gathering evidence; it will publish its recommendations and findings in sprin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g 2014, and these will include definitive guidelines for charity trustees to take into account when setting salaries. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Employees in charities and the voluntary sector</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An estimated 732,000 people were employed in the voluntary sector in the UK during 2011,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> equivalent to 2.7% of the UK workforce.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number of people employed in the sector in 2011 was 34% greater than in 2001, representing an increase of around 185,000 employees.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Most of these people worked for charities, but the term voluntary sector is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">broad; for example it also includes employees of trusts and trade unions.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are 163,000 registered charities in England and Wales.  Of these, 120,000 charities have an annual income of less than £100,000 and 1,900 have an annual income of over £5 m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illion.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">    </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Charities with, essentially, an income of more than £500,000 are currently required to show in their annual accounts the number of staff whose remuneration for the year fell within each </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">salary band of £10,000 from £60,000 upwards.  These chari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ty accounting requirements (known as the Statement of Recommended Practice or SORP) are currently under review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The professionalization of the charity sector, has continued apace over the past 20 years; a trend accelerated by the increasing role of chariti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es in delivering public services, with 23 per cent of charities now citing the delivery of public services as their primary function.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Features of modern charities include; a professional approach to their operation and activities; an emphasis on demonstr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ating value for money; setting of performance targets, and the employment of professionally qualified staff.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the same time whilst the public continues to have high levels of trust in charities, compared with other organisations and institutions, their p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erception of what organisations are charities is much narrower than the reality.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For some time the issue of senior executive salaries across all sectors has been an area of public and political debate.  In particular, the last few months hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e seen the publication of numerous articles on the pay of senior staff working in charities. These articles followed on from similar articles on pay in the public sector and, in particular, the financial services industry.  This media coverage has generate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d significant interest and debate.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In particular, at the beginning of August this year the Daily Telegraph published an article,   ’30 charity chiefs paid more than £100,000’.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Responding to the article, NCVO’s Chief Executive, Sir Stuart Etherington, sa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">id “Charity trustees should set remuneration using a clear process, taking into account the demands of the job and comparable salaries, and they should be transparent about senior pay.”  He also announced that NCVO would set up an Inquiry to conduct a revi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ew into the issue and develop guidance for charities on how they should set senior staff salaries.   Shortly afterwards NCVO published further details about the Executive Pay Inquiry.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">NCVO Executive Pay Inquiry</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst the Inquiry has been convened by NC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">VO it is charged with recommending, from an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">independent perspective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, principles and arguments that should guide Trustees as they set pay levels for senior executives in the voluntary sector; having:  </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">explored the arguments about what are appropriate level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s of pay for charity senior executives and how these levels should be arrived at; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">examined the relationship between salary levels and public trust and confidence in the sector.</span></li></ul><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Inquiry is chaired by Martyn Lewis CBE, Chair of NCVO.  A full list of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the members of the Inquiry Panel is attached to this submission; and the membership includes people who represent a cross-section of charities, as well as remuneration and HR specialists.  One of the Charity Commission board members, as well as the Commiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion’s Head of Policy, are attending the Inquiry meetings as observers, and they are contributing evidence from the regulator’s case work and their regulatory experience.  All of the Inquiry Panel members are serving in a voluntary capacity.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As part of it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s work the Inquiry is speaking to:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.96pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Donors, including those who have changed their behaviour because of concerns about executive pay</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.96pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Trustees and staff working in large and small charities </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.96pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Remuneration specialists</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.96pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Politicians</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.96pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Think Tanks and specialist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research organisations</span></li></ul><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Inquiry has also invited people to submit evidence and contributions using a dedicated email address.  To date, the Inquiry has received over 100 submissions via this route.      </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Taking account of all of these views, and the wid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er context and debate, the Inquiry’s initial discussion has focussed on:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The principles that should underpin senior executive pay and remuneration;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The value that is attached to working for a charity, and whether a ‘charity discount’ does or should apply; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The changing profile of the charity sector and the possible implications for executive pay; for example the potential impact of charities’ changing role in public service delivery, and the creation of new charities such as academies and former public b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">odies;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Definitions of pay, including the difference between a base salary and a total reward package; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of comparators, ratios and benchmarking when looking at pay;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The relationship between levels of executive pay and public trust and confidence in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> charities;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The perspective of beneficiaries, donors and other stakeholders;  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Transparency of reporting arrangements for senior executive pay; and   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.81pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Developments in other sectors; including for example the new requirements for quoted companies directors’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> remuneration reports that were introduced in October this year.</span></li></ul><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Inquiry will conclude its work in spring 2014 when it will publish its recommendations and definitive guidelines for charity trustees to take into account when setting salaries. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Pay Inquiry Panel </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lord (Charles) Allen of Kensington CBE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, outgoing Chairman of the Red Cross, Chairman of the Olympic Legacy charity “Join In” and Global Radio Group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sir John Baker CBE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Former Chair of the Senior Salaries Review Body </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(SSRB) and subsequent chair of an Independent Review into parliamentary pay, pensions and allowances.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Nick Brooks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Partner and Head of not-for-profit sector group at accountancy firm Kingston Smith.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Andrew Dent CVO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Chair of the volunteering charity REACH.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><s